  "Idea": "The proposed idea, Semantic-Prior Augmented Prototype Adversary (SPAPA), introduces a novel generative adversarial framework for few-shot learning that integrates large language model (LLM)-derived semantic priors into the construction of class-specific, probabilistic prototypes to guide the generation of high-quality, generalizable embeddings. While PCLSA leverages data-aggregated Gaussian prototypes to avoid memorization, SPAPA enhances this paradigm by infusing external semantic knowledge—extracted via zero-shot prompting of LLMs—into the prototype formation process. For each class name or definition, we query an LLM (e.g., Llama-3 or Mistral) to generate a rich semantic descriptor encompassing attributes, functional roles, contextual associations, and taxonomic relations. These descriptors are encoded into a semantic vector space using a frozen sentence encoder (e.g., Sentence-BERT), forming a 'prior prototype'. Concurrently, an empirical prototype is computed from support set embeddings as in PCLSA. A lightweight prototype modulation network then fuses these two sources—empirical and prior—into a unified probabilistic prototype (Gaussian mean and diagonal covariance) through a confidence-gated attention mechanism that weighs their contributions based on data availability and semantic coherence. The generator samples from the latent space conditioned on this hybrid prototype, producing embeddings that reflect both observed data patterns and broader conceptual knowledge. The discriminator evaluates whether generated embeddings conform to the fused prototype distribution and maintains semantic fidelity via a projected cosine similarity in the semantic descriptor space. A new triple-objective loss combines: (1) adversarial alignment with the prototype distribution, (2) semantic consistency loss enforcing proximity between generated embeddings and their LLM-derived semantic vectors, and (3) uncertainty-aware regularization that penalizes overconfident deviations inconsistent with either source. This design enables the model to generate embeddings that are not only statistically plausible but also semantically meaningful, even for classes with minimal or ambiguous visual instances. SPAPA excels in extreme few-shot and zero-shot transfer scenarios, particularly where classes have strong linguistic definitions but limited visual exemplars (e.g., rare species, abstract concepts). By grounding generative imagination in external knowledge, SPAPA moves beyond pure data-driven hallucination toward cognitively informed synthesis, offering a scalable, interpretable, and generalizable solution for low-data representation learning.",
